  <mainDescription>&lt;a id=&quot;XE_Best_Practices__Evolve_to_Complex&quot; name=&quot;XE_Best_Practices__Evolve_to_Complex&quot;>&lt;/a> &#xD;
&lt;table bordercolor=&quot;#ffffff&quot; width=&quot;100%&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;tbody>&#xD;
        &lt;tr>&#xD;
            &lt;td width=&quot;23%&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;h3 dir=&quot;ltr&quot;>&#xD;
                    Introduction&#xD;
                &lt;/h3>&#xD;
                &lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
                    It is a well known fact that it is impossible to define a complex system in one fell swoop. Start&#xD;
                    simple and iterate towards the final definition, perhaps over many iterations and releases.&amp;#160;&#xD;
                &lt;/p>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td width=&quot;4%&quot;>&#xD;
                &amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
            &lt;td width=&quot;73%&quot;>&#xD;
                &lt;table style=&quot;HEIGHT: 258px; WIDTH: 621px&quot; bordercolor=&quot;#000000&quot; cellpadding=&quot;5&quot; width=&quot;621&quot; border=&quot;3&quot;>&#xD;
                    &lt;tbody>&#xD;
                        &lt;tr>&#xD;
                            &lt;td width=&quot;16%&quot;>&#xD;
                                &lt;strong>Benefits&lt;/strong>&#xD;
                            &lt;/td>&#xD;
                            &lt;td width=&quot;84%&quot;>&#xD;
                                &lt;ul>&#xD;
                                    &lt;li>&#xD;
                                        Productivity&#xD;
                                    &lt;/li>&#xD;
                                    &lt;li>&#xD;
                                        Early business benefit&#xD;
                                    &lt;/li>&#xD;
                                    &lt;li>&#xD;
                                        Realistic plans&#xD;
                                    &lt;/li>&#xD;
                                    &lt;li>&#xD;
                                        Increased agility and adaptability&#xD;
                                    &lt;/li>&#xD;
                                &lt;/ul>&#xD;
                            &lt;/td>&#xD;
                        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
                        &lt;tr>&#xD;
                            &lt;td>&#xD;
                                &lt;strong>Pattern&lt;/strong>&#xD;
                            &lt;/td>&#xD;
                            &lt;td>&#xD;
                                &lt;ul>&#xD;
                                    &lt;li>&#xD;
                                        Enable feedback by delivering incremental user value&amp;#160;&#xD;
                                    &lt;/li>&#xD;
                                    &lt;li>&#xD;
                                        Adapt the architecture using an iterative process&#xD;
                                    &lt;/li>&#xD;
                                    &lt;li>&#xD;
                                        Embrace and manage change&#xD;
                                    &lt;/li>&#xD;
                                    &lt;li>&#xD;
                                        Attack major technical, business and programmatic risks early&#xD;
                                    &lt;/li>&#xD;
                                    &lt;li>&#xD;
                                        Define an appropriate scope and level of detail&amp;#160;&#xD;
                                    &lt;/li>&#xD;
                                &lt;/ul>&#xD;
                            &lt;/td>&#xD;
                        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
                        &lt;tr>&#xD;
                            &lt;td>&#xD;
                                &lt;strong>Anti-Patterns&lt;/strong>&#xD;
                            &lt;/td>&#xD;
                            &lt;td>&#xD;
                                &lt;ul>&#xD;
                                    &lt;li>&#xD;
                                        The complete architecture in detail&#xD;
                                    &lt;/li>&#xD;
                                    &lt;li>&#xD;
                                        Assess the solution/architecture by relying on reviews of specifications, rather&#xD;
                                        than feedback from projects.&#xD;
                                    &lt;/li>&#xD;
                                    &lt;li>&#xD;
                                        Always see more process and more detail as better&#xD;
                                    &lt;/li>&#xD;
                                &lt;/ul>&#xD;
                            &lt;/td>&#xD;
                        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
                    &lt;/tbody>&#xD;
                &lt;/table>&#xD;
            &lt;/td>&#xD;
        &lt;/tr>&#xD;
    &lt;/tbody>&#xD;
&lt;/table>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Discussion&amp;#160;&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;span&#xD;
    style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: 'Arial','sans-serif'; mso-fareast-font-family: 'Times New Roman'; mso-ansi-language: EN-CA; mso-fareast-language: EN-CA; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA&quot;>In&#xD;
    the UAM context, an iteration may include the implementation phase; the deployment of a first, second, or “n” releases&#xD;
    of the architecture and system, refining each time. The right level of detail for any architecture effort is based upon&#xD;
    the context and also the participants:&amp;#160;&lt;/span>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Level of knowledge of the enterprise or domain in question;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The level of experience of the architect;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The scope of the architectural effort.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;span&#xD;
    style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: 'Arial','sans-serif'; mso-fareast-font-family: 'Times New Roman'; mso-ansi-language: EN-CA; mso-fareast-language: EN-CA; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA&quot;>Defining&#xD;
    a complete enterprise in “an excruciating level of detail”, as John Zachman states, is just not possible, practical nor&#xD;
    useful. But defining the architecture for a small business domain in great detail may be useful and possible. Ideally&#xD;
    one does have all the detail, since it is much easier to understand impacts of change and implement change when one has&#xD;
    the complete picture in all the gory detail (e.g., Boeing revising the 747 design to define the 747-8 model—not&#xD;
    possible if the detail had not been available). This is the ultimate goal for the architect, a high-level of detail,&#xD;
    but which can only be attained over a long period of time and much iteration. Therefore, in each situation, finding the&#xD;
    appropriate level of detail and layering of architectures definitions is very important.&amp;#160;&lt;/span>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    It is a judgment call based upon the factors mentioned above—but err on the side of reduced detail since more can be&#xD;
    added over time. Over time the tools available for doing IT architecture (and subsequent implementation) will improve,&#xD;
    permitting more detail.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Will we ever get to the Zachman nirvana—not likely in our lifetimes?&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
</org.eclipse.epf.uma:PracticeDescription>
